%S A101747 3,4,5,6,7,19,40,56,93
%N A101747 Numbers k such that ((0!)^2+(1!)^2+(2!)^2+...+(k!)^2)/6 is prime.
%C A101747 Let S(k) = Sum_{i=0,..k} (i!)^2. Note that 6 divides S(k) for k>1. For prime p=20879, p divides S(p-1). Hence p divides S(k) for all k >= p-1 and all prime values of S(k)/6 are for k < p-1. These k yield provable primes for k <= 93. No other k < 4000.
%C A101747 No other k < 8000. [_T. D. Noe_, Jul 31 2008]
%p A101747 S:= proc(k) local i; add((i!)^2,i=0..k) end proc:
%p A101747 select(k -> isprime(S(k)/6), [$2..100]); # _Robert Israel_, Jan 25 2026
%t A101747 f2=1; s=2; Do[f2=f2*n*n; s=s+f2; If[PrimeQ[s/6], Print[{n, s/6}]], {n, 2, 100}]
%t A101747 Flatten[Position[Accumulate[Table[(n!)^2/6,{n,0,100}]],_?(PrimeQ[#]&)]]-1 (* _Harvey P. Dale_, Jan 09 2026 *)
%Y A101747 Cf. A061062 (S(n)), A100288 (primes of the form S(n)-1), A100289 (n such that S(n)-1 is prime), A101746 (primes of the form S(n)/6).
